 care the dii\nabled soldier receives, men who ai\ncrippled and maimed as the result t\nprotecting us?the men who we mus\ncomfort and protect to the best of on\nability.\"\nMr. McLeod said he had made\npersonal investigation and had foun\nout that Samuel Vaniella was an or\nderiy in ward 33 at the time of th\nfire. He said the patients were sur\nposed to be searched repeatedly befoi\ngoing to their rooms. This was nc\ndone on the morning of the tire, li\nquoted Vaniella as saying.\nHe explained to the committee th\nbest information he had received r<\ngar'ding the conditions at the time c\nthe fire. He said that while there is n\nsmoking in the insane ward, he hint\nself, while accompanied by three oth\"\nwitnesses, saw soldiers smoking whil\nhe was in the ward.\nFinds Explosive* I fiprot ertrd.\nRepresentative McDeod also calle\nthe attention of the committee to th\nfact that a week ago there was an\nother fire at Walter Reed Ho^ita\nand that there is a great deal of al\ncohol and other explosive chemical\nthere which are unprotected.\nRepresentative McLeod told the com\nmittee that in the two insane ward\nwhich were destroyed there were be\ntween forty and fifty patients. H\nsaid that his characterization of Wal\nter Reed Hospital as \"one of th\ngreatest fire-traps in the country\nwas quoting from a statement hv th\ncommander of the American Legion.\nEdwin M. Cleary emotionally urge\nupon the committee that the situatio\nat Walter Reed is extremely danger\nous. and that it is imperative tha\nCongress should see that greate\nprotection is afforded to the 1.400 wa\nheroes. He laid before the committe\na letter which he had written t\nChairman Mapes of the House Distrir\ncommittee making recommendation\nfor better service by the fire depart\nment. and a reply from Commissione\nHendrfck. which he said practicall\nignored the recommendations.\nESCH PROPOSAL TO AMENt\nWATER POWER LAW IS UF\nHouse Committee Hearing on Pro\nViLiai TT? -e\nluuiuug use 01 rars waters tor\nDevelopment Projects.\nRepresentative Esau's proposet\namendment to the water power law, pro\nhibiting use of waters within nations\nparka for hydro-electric developments\nwas the subject of a hearing- before th\nHouse Interstate Commerce committer\nyesterday. Director Mather of the na\ntional park service, told the committee\nmen the Interior*Department was agree\nable to having the prohibition apply t\nthe present boundaries of the parks'am\nnot to areas contiguous to them whicl\nlater might be taken in as addition.'\nSecretary Payne indorsed the proposa\nto bar development in the parks, whicl\nhe said, might mar their scenic beauty\nSecretary Baker, a member of th\nfederal power commission, said he di<\nnot favor changing the amendment t\nmake it apply only to present boundarie\nof parks, but Secretary Meredith, th\nother member of the commission, sai<\nhe did.\nSome members of the committee ex\npressed the feeling that the Esch amend\nment as drawn would not preclude de\nveiopment in the contiguous areas, bu\nHenry J. Pierce, president of the Wash\nington Irrigation and Development Com\npany, who appeared representing tl.\npower companies, which supply two\nthirds of the population on the Paoifl\nslope, thought It might, and referring t\nDirector Mather, drew out the state\nment that the Interior Departmen\nwould be satisfied to have the amend\nment refer to present boundaries alone\nRepresentative Winslow, republican\nof Massachusetts, saying he wished ti\nlearn the opinion of those \"not inter\nested In water power development,'\nasked Mr. Pierce if he had any testi\nmony on the subject from the people a\nlarge, on the Pacific slope to suppor\nhis'view. Mr.- Pierce replied that h\ncould if desired furnish abundant proo\nthat the public there favored the re\nsection as accepted by the park service\n^OHN BliRKE RETIRES.\nTreasurer of U. S. Will Join Neu\nYork Banking: Concern.\nJohn Burke, treasurer of the Lnite:\nStates since 1913. retired today, hi;\nresignation having been accepted b;\nPresident Wilson. Mr. Burke has en\ntered a New York banking firm.\nGuy P. Allen, assistant treasurer\nbecame acting treasurer on Mr\nBurke's retirement, and it wa;\nlearned that President Wilson doe,\nnot contemplate making an appoint\nment to the vacancy, leaving it to bi\nfilled by President-elect Harding.\nSEES TOO MANY BUREAUS\nJohns Hopkins President State:\nCause of Business Depression.\nBALTIMORE. January 7 (Special).?\nThe present business depression h\ndue in large measure to the multipli\ncation ?of government bureaus anc\nagencies and the resulting increase:\nim tavaiinn hnth hv tlio etafn rrnir\nHI .MIA?VIWII| v??v DVBI.C feWY\neraments and the national govern\nment according: to Dr. J. F. Goodnowpreaident\nof the Johns 'Hopkins Unh\nversity. Such measures, he says. ar<\nabsorbing; new capital and placing\na staggering burden on private en\nterprises on which the people depern\nfor their living. They are also rais\ning prices, he thinks.\n\"I do not believe that the countrj\nwill be able to stand the burden o\ntaxation if the governments, stati\nand national, continue to multiple\ntheir agencies and the costs of theii\noperation,\" said Dr. Goodnow, \"am\nno new government enterprise shouh\nhe started in the next five or tei\nyears.\"\nr>\nI CARDS OF THAXK*.\nPAYNE. We desire to thank onr relative*.\nfiien-N :?i*tl ore.'11-y.at oiik for tlieir sympathy\nI ami benuiful floral tributes at the ueaib of j\nj our dear -:sier. F.MMA J. PAYXK. 1\nIIEI: I.KOTUKUS ANI> SISTKK*.\nI! SMTTH. We wish to extend to our relative*\nam! many ir emls our sincere thank-* for j\nthe r k ttatiess. sympathy nu.l beautiful fl.-ral j\nt.il u.es leiide.ed <Itir ulr the illness ami at\ntl?e death ??f ??ur beloved husband au-?\nfather. U I1,L1AM II li. S.ViITU\nrtlr: FAMILY i\n5 1)1 HI).\nAIDEN. Suddenly. Thursday. January lh'Jl.\nat AsJieville. N. KiJjKN I.. beloved wife\n\"f t'iiijtles s. Allen SiTvircs Samrdty, 1\nJ..i<ua y v. at tlaui- r's Chapel. 1