you a father? Love him well\nWhile he is spared to earth.\nWait not till death shall call him hence\n0 To know his precious worth.\nOh. soothe him in his hours of pain.\nBe gentle and be mild:\nHow sweet 'twill be for you to know\nYou've beeu u faithful child.\nDeath has robbed us of our father.\nOf the one we loved so well;\n5 Taken from this world of sorrow\nSafely home with Him to dwell.\nOone from earth, yes. gone fortvel*.\nTear-dimmed eyes will gaze in vain;\nWe will hear his voire, oh. never?\n3 Never more on earth again.\nHIS DAUGHTERS. ADDIE BROWN AND\nj EMMA BOOKER.\n5 There are loved ones in glory.\nWhose dear forms we often miss;\nWhen we close our earthly story\nWe hope to join them In their bliss.\nI One by one our home is emptied.\nOne by one they have gone away;\nNow the family has parted.\nBut will be complete some day.\nHIS DEVOTED SON. GEORGE BROWN.\n\"col. watterson not hi.\nr GALVESTON. Tex,. January 7.?\nf Reports that Col. Henry Watterson\ns was seriously ill at his hotel here\nf were emphatically denied by Mrs.\nr Watterson and the colonel's phyi\nsician last night. \"There Is nothing\nto It.\" Mrs. Watterson told the Asso.\ni elated Press over the telephone, when\ninformed of the rumor.\nIMKMORMv\nC A HILL. A tribute of love find devotion to\nm.-itiorj* of my door sister. KAU.IE A.\nII1I.L. who departed this lift? Of teen\nago today. January 7. 1WT?.\nHER SISTFU MAlUiARET V, t llX. i\nCIIANEY. In sa.l but loving remembrance of\nI my unsbaad. 1IKNUY CliAN'EV, who <lfI\n|>a? ted fiow ?h s life January 7, lfl'Jit.\nI stood by Ins liedside.\nI saw iiis noui depart,\nAm! when I ica.ined be was dead\ni It almost broke my heart\nDays of s.idiu-ss st.U come oVr mc.\ntii'tdeii t/'?rs so often flow.\nMen.o-r keeps my husband near me.\nAlthough he died (tic .war ago.\nIlls ],1?Y1N<; Will-; AM? AINT. LENA\nI 11ANKY AND IDA.\nHARDI2T. In loving memory of my huslmnd.\n\\N 1I.K1AM L HARDIN, whom death claimed\ni one jrsi ago today. January 7. IbllO.\ni As deaf men crave for sound and blind f-?r\nsight.\nAs \\v?aiy sons of toil long for the right.\nAnd a- the fettered spirit longs for flight,\nj I long for tliee.\nlt.;t iI;ou art gone, not lost, but flown.\nShall I (hen a>k the.- hark, my own'.*\nlt??k and leave thy spirit's brightness,\nj Rack and leave tny riii?-s of whiteness.\nRack and leave thy h?nven1v Father.\nHack to earth and sin? No. rather\n1 Would I live in solitude.\ni m<?ii 141 not ask iliee if I could\nRui, patient. wait the h'gh decree\nChat rall? my spirit h?*ur to thee.\nI shall not cry Return! Return!\nitut just as long as sunset* burn\nAnd d.iwus make no delay.\n1 shall lie lonesome* I shall mis*\nYour hand, your voire, v??ur smile. tour kiss.\nHIS WIFi:. MARGARET HARDIN\nThe door. I know, is just a>ar between hi*\nworld and mine;\nThe time I know cannot be far when our\ndear ones we'll ttnd:\nItcsld\" the gates 1 know he wait*\n4 For those he left Iiehind.\nII1S SISTKlt IN LAW 8ARAH.\nHARDIN. In id but loving rcmembran<-e of\nour brother-in law and uncle. WILLIAM\nHARDIN. who departed this life one year\nago today. January 7. 192b.\nWhen you departed the sun was high and\nbright.\nAnd yon passed to heaven before the coming\nof ti ght;\nA beautiful smile played o'er your face a*\nyou saw the light,\nj Hut only trust**! Cod to lead you safely\nalong the wav.\nSlSTira IN LAW ANNA.\nHORNILL. In loving renienibranee of IALLIAN\nHORNII.L. who departed this life one\nyear ago today. January 7. 192b.\nIf we had seen her at the last\nAnd herld her gentle hand.\nAnd heard the sigh from her heart.\ne would not feel so sad.\nWe did not know the pain she bore.\nAnd did not see her die;\nWe only know she went away\nAnd did not siv good-bye.\nIIKit AtWT AMI GR ANDMOTflEIt. MART\nK. AND HK1.LK DIKTZ.\nINGRAM. In memoty of our faithful and\ndevoted aunt. MARTHA INGRAM, who died\none year ago toda January 7. 192b.\nShe lived for those who loved her.\nWhose hearts were foud and true.\nHAITIK. RICHARD. 1'AKKKK.\nJOHNSON. Sacred to the memory of mj dear\ncousin, LOriSK JOHNSON, who entered into\neternal teat two years ago today, January\n7. 191S.\nThe depth of my sorrow I cannot tell.\nAt the loss of one 1 loved so well.\nAnd while she lies in peaceful sleep\nThe memory of her 1 will always keep.\nMore and more each day I miss you.\nFriends may think the wound is healed.\nHut little do tliey know the sorrow\nThat lie* in iny heart concealed.\nHLK DKVOTKD COUSIN. RLKANOR MA\nLONE.\ni JOHNSON. Sacred to the memory of our devoted\nmother. MATILDA LEE JOHNSON,\nwho died two years ago. January 7, 1919.\ni KROPP. In loving remembrance of my dear\nuj.;li.rr, daiuiaua KKOPP. who died four\nyears ago today, Januaiy 7. 1917.\nj Dear mother, you have slept another year,\ni?ut we know not whore;\nI only know it's beautiful.\nFor you sleep with Jesus there.\nI Your sleep is so sweet I would not wake you.\nYet I Jong to have you here;\nI Your loving smile and tenderness\nMade sunshine everywhere,\nj In this land of sorrow.\nWhere friends are so few,\nj Mother, dear mother,\nI How I iniss you.\nj HER LOVING DAUGHTER.\nKROPP. In sad but loving remembrance of\nmy mother. KAKItARA KROPP. who died\nfour year* ago today, January 7, 1917.\nj Just a thought of sweet remembrance,\nj Just a memory fond and true;\ni Just a token of appreciation\nI And a heartache still for you.\nMay the heavenly winds blow softly\nj Over the sweet and hallowed spot;\n*'Mid the changing scenes of life, mother,\n1 You will never be forgot. llElt SON.\nLONG. In sad remembrance of our darling.\nMAUDE A. LONG tnee Laurie), who died\ntwo years ago today. January 7. 1919, and\nher loving husband. SAMUEL C. LONG,\nwho died January 4. 1919.\nI always think of you dear Maudie,\nAnd iuy heart is sad with pain;\nxms worm would l?e a heaven to me\nCould you be witli me again.\n1 never will forget you\nWhile here on earth I stay:\nGimI only knows uiy feelings\nSince you have passed away.\nGRANDMOTHER LAURIE.\nHer well remembered footsteps\nI We are listening for in vain,\nI And our eyes grow dim with watching\nAnd our hearts are sad with pain.\nA shadow rests upon our home.\nWe miss her well loved face:\nWhere'er we turn, where'er we look.\nWe see her vacant place.\nAUNT MAUDE.\nPOOLE. In sad but loving remembrance of\nmy dear father, VIRGIL T. POOLE, who\ndeparted this lite two years ago, January 7,\n1919.\nDays of sadness come o'er me.\nSacred tears do often flow.\nBut memory keep you ever near me.\nThough you died two years ago.\nHIS LOVING SON. JOHN 8. 1*00LE.\nWOOD. A tribute of love'to the memory of\nour dear father and grandfather, GEORGE\nW. WOOD, who departed thia life nine years\nago today, January 7, 19111.\nHis sacred memory still remains within\nour hearts,\nHIS DAUGHTER. MARTHA E. TUCKER.\nAND G RANDDAUGHTEK. E88IE TI CKER.\nFUNERAL DIRECTORS.\nV. L. SPEARE~CO;?\n(NEITHER THE SUCCESSORS OF HOI COS\nNECTED WITH THE ORIGINAL W.\nSFEARE ESTABLISHMENT.)\nFfcono Frankiln 6888. WF A m.w.\nJ. WILLIAM LEE. Funeral Director\nand embalmei. Lively In connection, rwi\ndiona chapel and modern crematorium. Moderate\npricea. 332 Pa. are. n.w. Tel. call. M. 1IU.\nFrank Geicr's Sons Co*,\nIlls SEVENTH STREET N.W.\nModern Chapel. Telephone call. North SS>\nTimothy Hanlon\n641 H ST. N.E. Phone L. 5841\nQuick. Dignified and Eflleieat Service.\nW. We Deal Co.\n818 H ST. N.E. Lincoln MM.\nAntomoblle Serrlce. Chapel.\nZUKHUKbT\n301 East Capitol Street\nPhone I.inroln 37Establlshed\nIn Martinsville, Iat.\n1837\nJAMES T. RYAN,\nS17 PA. AVE. S.B.\nMoiern Chapel. Lis cols 1U.\nPrirate Ambulances.\nLivery In ronneetlon.\nf\n^VL08'H\n(FoaMEKLY o<oF?tNJnrX\nPHONE-WE^MN IOa\njg]$peare. OBUxifc 1?\nJoseph F. Birch's Sons\n3034 M St. N.W 1?Antomobtle\nftervtea.\nWE H. SARDO CO?\n412 B ?t. n.e. Phone Llneala 684.\nModern Chapel. Automobile Ftoerate.\nCEMETERIES.\nFort Lincoln perpetual eonoffmai!\nBaltimore Boulerard at DlatHat Idle.\nOWcet: 828 14th at. ?-W. Phoae r. 4T4A\nOTNERAL DESIQH8.\nGude Bros. Co* 1214 F 